Population structure: practical

Lewis Spurgin

Introduction

In this practical we will be analysing population structure in a genomic dataset. By the end of the practical you should be able to employ some commonly used methods (FST, admixture, PCA) to detect and quantify population structure. We will also continue to developing our plotting skills in R.

The data

We will be using a large SNP dataset from nine European great tit populations to explore continental-scale genomic structure. The data are stored as binary plink files in the “population_structure” folder.

Data exploration and cleaning in plink

In the genomic diversity practical we assumed that our data was cleaned and ready to go. However, this is usually not the case! We may have markers that are not in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium in our datset, markers that are in high LD, or highly related individuals. These may invalidate the assumptions of some of our analyses. It is important that, for each analysis, we check our assumtpions ensure that our data does not violate them. Plink has lots of great functions that enable us to clean our datasets. Before looking at population structure, we are going to do some data cleaning.

Before we clean our data, ese the command line to explore .bed, .bim and .fam files to try to figure out how many individuals and SNP markers have been typed.

You will remember from the last practical that we calculated heterozygosity and HWE for every locus in our flour beetle data. We can do the same thing in plink. Further, we can get plink to automatically generate a list of markers that are exceed a given Hardy-Weinberg P value threshold, and then filter our dataset to either exclude or include these loci. Let’s aim to exclude loci with a Hardy-Weinberg p value < 0.01. Can you figure out from the plink manual how we might do this on our GreatTits .bed file?

plink --bfile GreatTits --hwe 0.01 --make-bed --out GreatTitsFiltered

Have a look at this output - how many individuals and loci went into the analysis? How many were written to the output file? Note the use of the option --make-bed at the end. This option generates a binary plink file as its output.

We will also filter based on minor allele frequencies. Can you find the command to exclude all loci with a minor allele frequency < 0.05? Why might we want to do this?

plink --file GreatTits --hwe 0.01 --maf 0.05 --make-bed --out GreatTitsFiltered

Note how we can add both --hwe and --maf options to a single command and used the same output name. This is more efficient and saces us space.

We will now “prune” our markers based on LD. Check out the options that plink has for this. See if you can figure out how to prune markers, using appropriate thresholds. You should perform this on the “GreatTitsFiltered” binary plink files you have just created. Then take a look what I have chosen below:

plink --bfile GreatTitsFiltered --indep-pairwise 50 10 0.05 --make-bed --out GreatTitsFiltered

I have chosen to prune in windows of 50 markers, shifting this window along 10 markers at a time. This is called a sliding window, and is somethig we will cover in more detail later in the course. The final argument (0.05) is the R^2 threshold of I chosen to prune with.Note that you can also use the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF), using the argument --indep. If you have chosen different thresholds that’s fine, but for now run the code with mine so we’re all working from the same data. This argument has written two lists of SNPs as output files - one list of SNPs in linkage equilibrium with one another, and one list of SNPs to be excluded. We can use either of these to filter our binary plink file to create a new dataset only containing markers in linkage equilibrium.

plink --bfile GreatTitsFiltered --extract GreatTitsFiltered.prune.in --make-bed --out GreatTitsFilteredPruned

Finally, we can filter based on individual relatedness. This is best done by expecting patterns of pairwise relatedness on your dataset, but for the sake of time we will pick a cut-off of 0.4, in order to remove full sibs (why not 0.5?).

plink --bfile GreatTitsFiltered --rel-cutoff 0.4 --out GreatTitsFilteredPruned
plink --bfile GreatTitsFiltered --keep GreatTitsFilteredPruned.rel.id --make-bed --out GreatTitsFilteredPrunedUnrel

We have rushed through this a little, but you should now have an idea about some of the processes that you can use to tidy your SNP data.

Pairwise FST

Let’s now focus on looking at population structure. In the “population_structure” folder, you should be able to find a file called “pairwise_fst_plink.py” Take a look at this file using nano.

nano pairwise_fst_plink.py

Can you work out what this python script is doing? Take a few minutes to go through each line and try to understand what it is achieving. Discuss with a colleague.

We are now going to run this script on our pruned and cleaned dataset to calculate pairwise FST for each of our population pairs. But you need to check that the name of your plink file (the bit before the “.bed” extension) exactly matches the string defined in the second line of the python script. If it does, either edit your file name or the script accordingly. Exit nano by pressing ctrl+X, enter Y when asked to save and then press enter, if you have made any edits to the script. You should now be able to run the script.

python pairwise_fst_plink.py

Take a look at the output from the python script(either using cat or nano), and make sure you understand the format of the output (hint - explore the python script and discuss with your colleagues). We will later use this output to create an isolation by distance plot, but for now we will run some extra population structure analyses on the server.

PCA

We can also use plink to generate a PCA of our genetic data. Again, we will use the pruned and cleaned dataset we generated earlier. Can you figure out how to run a PCA on this data, in which you keep the first four principal components?

plink --bfile GreatTitsFilteredPrunedUnrel --pca 4 --out GreatTitsFilteredPrunedUnrel

Have a look at the output files and check you are happy with what you have got (hint - use the plink manual). Again, we will download our file for plotting soon.

Admixture

Finally, we are going to run Admixture on our dataset. But first we need to do one more piece of cleaning. We still have a very large number of SNPs in our great tit dataset, and with this many individuals and SNPs it would take Admixture several hours to run. So we aree going to thin our markers substantially for the purpose of this practical. Can you figure out, using plink, how to randomly select 1% of your markers and write them to a new file?

plink --bfile GreatTitsFilteredPrunedUnrel --thin 0.01 --make-bed --out GreatTitsThinned

Now look up the admixture manual online. The software has been installed on the server, and can be called up by typing admixture. If you do this, you will see that at its most basic level you just need an input file and a value of K. We will stick with the program defaults for now. Try running admixture at k = 2 for your cleaned great tit dataset, using the following code.

mkdir admixture #So current directory doesn't get too messy
cd admixture
admixture ../GreatTitsThinned.bed 2

Have a look at your outputs - you should see a file ending in “.P”, and one ending in “.Q”. Explore these files and see if you can figure out what each one is.

Typically with software like STRUCTURE or admixture, we wish to compare how genetic variation is structured across multiple values of k - usually from k = 2 to k = \(N_{populations}\). We could do this by repeating the above command 8 times, with k ranging from 2 to 9. But a more efficient way would be to create a for loop in bash. Can you figure out how to do this?

for K in `seq 2 9`;
do
  admixture ../GreatTitsThinned.bed $K;
done

Done! Now we can download all of our results and do some plots. You will need to download: - The pairwise FST output from the python script - The file LatLong.txt - The output from your plink PCA (the “.eigenvec” file) - All of your admixture “.Q” files - The file “GreatTitsThinned.fam” - The R script “Admixture_plot.R”

Our next task is to calculate pairwise distance between each of our populations. We could go to Google maps and do this manually, but thankfully we can do it in R! Have a look at the distGeo() function in the geosphere library:

library(geosphere)
?distGeo

distGeo() calculates the pairwise distance between two points - all you need to do is give it the longitude and latitude of the two points. We have longitude and latitude information in the file “LatLong.txt”. Read this file into R and take a look at it.

Let’s try calculating the distance in metres between the first pair of populations in our pd data frame, Mariola_Spain and Pirio_Muro_Corsica. We will first extract the latitude and longitude information for each of these populations, then use the distGeo() function to calculate the distance between them.

#Extract population names from pd data frame
pop1 <- pd$p1[1] #First element of p1 column
pop2 <- pd$p2[1] #First element of p2 column

#Get lat and log information
l1 <- subset(ll,Pop == pop1)
l2 <- subset(ll,Pop == pop2)

#Now calculate distance
distGeo(p1 = c(l1$Long,l1$Lat),p2 = c(l2$Long,l2$Lat))
## [1] 965860.9

That looks about right! Now we need to calculate the distance between all of the population pairs in our data frame. Below I provide one ways that you can do this - using a for loop (DISCLAIMER - this is not the most efficient way of doing this, but it works). Discuss with your colleagues how you think the code is working.

#Create an empty distance column
pd$dist <- NA

#Loop over the pd data frame
for(i in 1:nrow(pd))
{

#Extract population names from pd data frame
pop1 <- pd$p1[i] #First element of p1 column
pop2 <- pd$p2[i] #First element of p2 column

#Get lat and log information
l1 <- subset(ll,Pop == pop1)
l2 <- subset(ll,Pop == pop2)

#Now calculate distance
pd$dist[i] <- distGeo(p1 = c(l1$Long,l1$Lat),p2 = c(l2$Long,l2$Lat))

}

#Check that it's worked

So bearing this in mind I though it would be good to show this group effect in my plot. Can you make a column in pd that tells us whether either of your populations is “Pirio_Muro_Corsica”?

pd$Comparison <- ifelse(pd$p1 == "Pirio_Muro_Corsica" | pd$p2 == "Pirio_Muro_Corsica", "Mainland-Island","Mainland-Mainland")

Now we can make the full plot. Note the use of scale_colour_manual() to change the colours we use in ggplot.

A <- ggplot(pd,aes(x = dist/1000,y = FST,col = Comparison))+ #divide by 1000 to get distance in km
      geom_point()+
      theme_bw()+
      xlab("Distance (km)")+
      ylab(expression("F"[ST]))+
      scale_colour_manual(values = c("black","grey"))

Now we are onto the tricky part - the admixture plots. Rather than take you through this step by step I have provided a function that I have written myself. This is in the “Admixture_plot.R” script that you downloaded. Open the script up and take a look at the code. We will not go into writing functions here, but essentially this script contains the code to create a function called admixtureplot(). After you have run the code in the script you will then be able to use the function. Running the code manually would work, but you would need to do this every time you ran the script you are currently working on. You could copy and paste the function code into your current script, but that would be rather unwieldy. We will use the following code:

source("~/Documents/Teaching/PopGenBerlinLGS/population_structure/Admixture_plot.R") #Or whatever the path to this script is

If you look in the “environment” tab in the top right of R studio, you should see that the admixtureplot() function has been loaded. You can call up the code by typing admixtureplot (without brackets) into the console.

Now we are ready to try running the function. admixtureplot has 4 arguments, three of which are mandatory. str_out is your “.Q” file from admixture, loaded into R as a data frame, “pops” is the “.fam” plink file associated with the “.bed” file used to run admixture. k is simply the value of k for the run, and xaxis is an optional argument with which we can tell the funciton whether or not to plot x axis labels.

Adapt the following code (depending on your working directory) to run the function for your K = 2 admixture output.

K2 <- read.table("~/Documents/Teaching/PopGenBerlinLGS/population_structure/admixture/GreatTitsThinned.2.Q")
mypops <- read.table("~/Documents/Teaching/PopGenBerlinLGS/population_structure/GreatTitsThinned.fam")
C <- admixtureplot(str_out = K2,k = 2, pops = mypops)

C

Now it should be fairly clear how we can do the same thing for K = 3 and 4, and thus create the plots in our original figure. Remember that we only want x axis labels for the K = 4 plot.

Now all we need to do is put our five plots together, using multiplot(). This is a bit more tricky is we have two plots on the left and three on the right. I will demonstrate how we will do this using layout(). To make a matrix for a 6-panel plot, we would do the following:

layout(matrix(1:6,ncol = 2))
layout.show(6)

A key feature or layout() is that plots can take up more than one panel. So, for example, if the three left-hand panels into a single plot, we could do the following:

layout(matrix(c(1,1,1,2:4),ncol = 2))
layout.show(4)

Bearing this in mind, see if you can figure out how to use layout() and layout.show() to produce a template for our 5-panelled figure, with two plots on the left and two on the right.

layout(matrix(c(1,1,1,2,2,2,3,3,4,4,5,5),ncol = 2))
layout.show(5)

What the above basically does is creates a matrix with six rows and two columns - the left-hand panels are given three rows, while the right=hand panels are given two.

This is almost there, but because only one of our three admixturew plots (the one due to go in panel 5) has x axis labels, we need to ascribe more space to this panel. Can you figure out a way to do this, and produce the layout shown below?

#12-row matrix
layout(matrix(c(1,1,2,2,3,4,5,5),ncol = 2))
layout.show(5)

Now we can use this layout within the multiplot() function to make our final figure: 
library(Rmisc)
multiplot(A,B,C,D,E,layout = matrix(c(1,1,2,2,3,4,5,5),ncol = 2))
